1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
The Lord of the Rings trilogy, if you see it back to back, it's good.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Dunder Mifflin, this is Pam.

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Pam, it's Michael. Help me. I need help right now.

4
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,000
Michael, what's wrong?

5
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,000
I'm hurt. I have hurt myself. Oh my God.

6
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:14,000
Okay, wait, wait, wait.

7
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:16,000
This is not looking good, Pam.

8
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:17,000
Michael, do you need me to call an ambulance?

9
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:19,000
No, I want you to pick me up.

10
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Okay, wait a second. I thought you said that you were hurt.

11
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:23,000
I am hurt. I hurt my foot.

12
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:27,000
I want to come to work, but I need you to come and pick me up.

13
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Oh God!

14
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Hey, whoa, Michael.

15
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,000
Oh God!

16
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:35,000
It's okay. It's Jim. Just say again really loudly what happened.

17
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Okay, I burned my foot very badly on my Foreman Grill,

18
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,000
and I now need someone to come and bring me into work.

19
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:46,000
You burned your foot on a Foreman Grill.

20
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,000
I enjoy having breakfast in bed.

21
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:51,000
I like waking up to the smell of bacon, sue me.

22
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:54,000
And since I don't have a butler, I have to do it myself.

23
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,000
So most nights before I go to bed,

24
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:00,000
I will lay six strips of bacon out on my George Foreman Grill.

25
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Then I go to sleep.

26
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
When I wake up, I plug in the grill.

27
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
I go back to sleep again.

28
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Then I wake up to the smell of crackling bacon.

29
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:13,000
It is delicious. It's good for me.

30
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:15,000
It's the perfect way to start the day.

31
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Today I got up, I stepped onto the grill,

32
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:20,000
and it clamped down on my foot. That's it.

33
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,000
I don't see what's so hard to believe about that.

34
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Can you come get me?

35
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:27,000
I have to stay here and answer the phone.

36
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Okay, could someone come and get me, please, Ryan?

37
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Michael, you should stay home and rest.

38
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
There's no toilet paper here. Could Ryan tell Ryan to bring toilet paper?

39
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
Could you tell him that?

40
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Can you hop?

41
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,000
I tried hopping, Kevin, and I bumped my elbow against the wall,

42
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,000
and now my elbow has a protuberance.

43
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:49,000
No one wants to pick me up?

44
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:52,000
What is going on?

45
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Michael is sick, and he wants one of us to rescue him.

46
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,000
I'm coming, Michael! I'm going to save you!

47
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Michael is in trouble! Okay?

48
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,000
Hold on, Michael! I am coming! Wait there!

49
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:05,000
I got it, Dwight!

50
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,000
Michael, why don't you call your girlfriend?

51
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:08,000
I don't have a girlfriend.

52
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,000
But you said you went out this weekend.

53
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,000
It was all made up. Just someone come, okay?

54
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Anyone, anyone but Dwight.

55
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,000
What was that?

56
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,000
What was that?

57
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Oh! He hit the pole!

58
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:28,000
It's broken, right? He can't...

59
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Oh, Dwight.

60
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:31,000
Dwight.

61
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:33,000
Oh!

62
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Oh my gosh!

63
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Is he okay?

64
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:38,000
He's still driving.

65
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Dwight!

66
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:42,000
You forgot your bumper!

67
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Hello?

68
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:46,000
Please don't send Dwight.

69
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,000
Morning, everyone.

70
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Don't freak out.

71
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
I forbid anybody to freak out.

72
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,000
Clearly, I have had a very serious accident,

73
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:32,000
but I will recover, God willing.

74
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,000
I just want to be treated normally today.

75
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,000
Normal would actually be good,

76
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
considering the trauma that I've been through.

77
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
You missed two big conference calls today, one with corporate.

78
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Oh, did you explain why?

79
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:45,000
No, I didn't mention that you cooked your foot.

80
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Burned my foot, Pam.

81
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,000
Please stop popping my cast.

82
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Thank you.

83
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:55,000
So where are you shipping your foot?

84
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Ha, ha, ha. So where are you shipping...

85
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Your foot?

86
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
You should put butter on it.

87
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
Uh, that's what she said.

88
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,000
See, I haven't lost my sense of humor.

89
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,000
No, no need. It was a nonstick grill.

90
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
I've had a Foreman grill for about six years.

91
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,000
I've done about 85% of my cooking on it.

92
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,000
But I've never burnt myself.

93
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
Probably because I don't use it as a pillow.

94
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,000
I always keep a stash of bubble wrap in my house.

95
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,000
Some days, hectic, tiring days,

96
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
I just like to go home and zone out,

97
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,000
click on the tube, and pop a few.

98
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:27,000
Very soothing.

99
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,000
Want to try?

100
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,000
You know, that's probably not going to last too long.

101
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
You should go to a hospital and get a real cast.

102
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:37,000
Right, like I'm going to spend the day in the hospital.

103
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:39,000
Bureaucracy and germs.

104
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:41,000
And doctors.

105
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Yes, so two days.

106
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:45,000
What?

107
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Constructing a homemade cast?

108
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Genius.

109
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Filled with foresight.

110
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Like in the pioneer times,

111
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
if you lost a leg,

112
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:57,000
they would then use the bone of the leg for a cane.

113
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:59,000
They wasted nothing.

114
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Wow, I don't want to hear you talk.

115
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Pam, can I have a word with you in my office?

116
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,000
Okay.

117
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,000
Oh.

118
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:09,000
All right.

119
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Thank you.

120
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,000
Pam, messages please.

121
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,000
You didn't have any.

122
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,000
Really?

123
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:19,000
Well, it seemed very important to you earlier

124
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
that you needed to stay and...

125
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
Do my job?

126
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,000
No.

127
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Your job is being my friend, Pam.

128
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,000
Ow! God!

129
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,000
It slipped.

130
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Sorry.

131
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,000
It's just that before you said you didn't want any special treatment.

132
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,000
I don't want any special treatment, Pam.

133
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
I just want you to treat me like you would

134
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:41,000
a family member who's undergone

135
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:43,000
some sort of serious physical trauma.

136
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:45,000
I don't think that's too much to ask.

137
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:47,000
Do you want some aspirin because you seem a little fussy?

138
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,000
No, I don't want some aspirin. Yeah, I am fussy.

139
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:51,000
Aspirin's not going to do a damn thing.

140
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:53,000
I'm sitting here with a bloody stump of a foot.

141
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,000
Pam, I am Assistant Regional Manager

142
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
and I can take care of him.

143
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,000
Part of my duties are to...

144
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:01,000
What? Part of your duties are to what?

145
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,000
What?

146
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:05,000
You just said that part of your duties are to something.

147
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,000
I didn't. Yes, you did.

148
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,000
What is wrong with you? What is wrong with you?

149
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:31,000
Oh, who made popcorn?

150
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,000
Well, you know,

151
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:41,000
frankly, a lot of us have been saying

152
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,000
something like this for a long time.

153
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,000
Yeah, I've been saying that.

154
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
Yeah, and I think that

155
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:49,000
the very fact that we're including it in our agenda,

156
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,000
frankly, is a big step forward.

157
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Did you know I used to be an HR?

158
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
I'm sorry? I used to be an HR.

159
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:57,000
I was a head of HR.

160
00:06:57,000 --> 00:06:59,000
I used to be an HR. I was a hellraiser.

161
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:01,000
Okay.

162
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:03,000
Right.

163
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:05,000
Great. Why don't we move on?

164
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:07,000
All right. Moving on.

165
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,000
Great, because I think that, you know, the very fact that...

166
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:11,000
Fine. Thank God. You're here.

167
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,000
What you got? What you got?

168
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
All right. Panic Room, Maverick,

169
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
now Summer's BBQs.

170
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,000
Where's little man Kate? Hey, we're out.

171
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:21,000
In three different places. Oh, man.

172
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:23,000
It's not a Jodie Foster afternoon without little man Kate, buddy.

173
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:29,000
Okay.
